observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:
a. Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal General Services Officer Designate with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;
b. Municipal General Services Officer Designate to maintain a complete Local Road Inventory and Road Map, Local Road Network Property Cards for all roads and their components and render a complete Report on Local Road Networks at the end of the year;
c. Inventory Committee, in coordination with the Municipal Engineering Office, to conduct physical inventory of all existing local road networks in the Municipality, prepare the corresponding Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network to be reconciled in the accounting records and LRNPC, and furnish a copy of the inventory report to the Audit Team for verification and audit;d. Municipal Accountant to:
1. Keep and maintain subsidiary records for road and road components for every road network with identified cost;
2. Prepare a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component at the end of the year; and
3. Disclose the total road networks in the Notes to Financial Statements in the format prescribed under COA Circular No. 2015-008.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
a. Inventory Committee to report the physical count of semi-expendable property owned by the agency, by type, and still in the custody Municipal General Services Office using the RPCSP;
b. Property and/or Supply Custodian to ensure that all issued semi-expendable properties are reported and summarized weekly using the RSPI, based on the ICS and to be used by the Accounting Office for preparing the journal entry voucher in compliance with COA Circular guidelines;
c. Instruct the Inventory Committee, the GSO Designate, and the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain all required forms, registry, and reports following the prescribed format to strengthen control over the semi-expendable properties; and
d. Require the Municipal Accountant to use the newly introduced accounts to record the purchase/acquisition and subsequent issuance of semi-expendable properties for fair presentation of the financial statements.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. Direct the GSO Designate to prepare and submit the consolidated PIF, which should include details such as the latest appraised values/valuations, insurable amounts, and corresponding premiums for all insurable properties and other assets of the Municipality, as required by COA Circular No. 2018-002;
b. Require the GSO Designate to process the application for insurance of all insurable assets and properties of the Municipality with the GSIS;
c. Instruct the Municipal Budget Officer to include in the Municipal’s Annual Budget the appropriation for the payment of insurance premiums for all insurable assets and properties of the Municipality; and
d. Direct the Municipal Accountant and Acting Municipal Treasurer to provide necessary assistance to the MGSO to ensure that all insurable assets and properties of the Municipality are covered by insurance in compliance with RA No. 656 and COA Circular No. 2018-002.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Acting Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to:
a. Conduct a thorough reconciliation among the BIR Forms, the GL, and the balances presented in the Statement of Financial Position to identify and correct any recording errors or omissions related to remittances made to the BIR, and to address the discrepancy of P1,989,172.82;
b. Investigate the unremitted balance of P650,720.58 and address any possible reasons for the under-remittance, whether it be due to clerical errors, oversight, or other factors;
c. Take immediate corrective action to remit the unremitted balance from prior periods, amounting to P650,720.58, to avoid the imposition of the 25 percent penalty, which could amount to P162,680.15, which may include working with the BIR to resolve any outstanding issues to minimize the financial impact; and henceforth,
d. Ensure the full and timely remittance of taxes withheld from employee compensation and payments to suppliers in compliance with the provisions of BIR Revenue Regulations No. 2-98 to avoid any penalties, surcharges, or interest.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. Instruct the GAD Focal Person to submit the GAD AR for CY 2024 and ensure that both the GPB and its corresponding GAD AR are submitted within the prescribed periods, to facilitate timely review and audit of GAD fund utilization;
b. Direct the GAD Focal Person to submit the GAD AR together with its required attachments, as mandated under Section 4.1.C.8 of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01, as amended, including:
1. A summary of the reported programs or projects;
2. Copies of relevant policy issuances;
3. Results of the Harmonized Gender and Development Guidelines (HGDG) tests; and
4. Actions taken by the LGU on previous COA audit findings and recommendations.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a) direct the Inventory Committee to complete the physical count and submission of RPCPPE for all types of PPE;
b) instruct the OIC- Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to maintain and update PPELC and PC, respectively, to facilitate reconciliation of the PPE accounts;
c) require the OIC- Municipal Accountant to identify the semi-expendable properties previously classified as PPE and prepare and submit a separate report for these items;
d) direct the Inventory Committee to adopt the guidelines and procedures for one-time cleansing of PPE account balances as provided by COA Circular No. 2020-006; and
e) henceforth, strictly observe compliance with pertinent provisions of MNGAS for LGUs and COA Circular No. 2020-006.

a. MGSO to submit to the Office of the Auditor the appraised value together with the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP), Appraisal Report and other required documents for appropriate action;
b. Appraisal and Disposal Committee to immediately undertake an appraisal of these unserviceable property and prepare a corresponding report thereon; and
c. Municipal Treasurer to initiate the process of disposing of unserviceable property in accordance with COA Circular No. 92-386 and drop these properties in the books based on the IIRUP.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:
a. Acting Municipal Accountant to:
• Submit immediately the lacking documents for the mentioned disbursements for further verification by the Audit Team;
• Refrain from recognizing as supplies those items classified as inventory, instead follow the recording and reporting procedures provided under Section 114 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I;
b. Municipal Treasurer to maintain the required reports for proper monitoring and reporting of the receipts and issuances of inventories and coordinate with the Acting Municipal Accountant for the proper amount of inventory that will be recognized as expense for a period;
c. Acting Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer or any appropriate Municipal official to coordinate with the Acting Municipal Accountant for the submission of the documents to substantiate the relief operations made by the Municipality and for the Audit Team to determine whether the procured relief supplies were completely distributed to the intended beneficiaries;
d. Municipal Budget Officer or any appropriate Municipal official to submit a written justification explaining the rationale for the charging of said disbursements totaling ₱66,680.00 against the BGCM fund; and
e. Concerned officials to comply with the posting requirement for transparency.

observations.managementAction:
a. The Acting Municipal Accountant had submitted the lacking documents for the mentioned disbursements for further verification by the Audit Team;
b. Delivery of supplies were issued directly to end-users after acceptance and delivery of the GSO;
c. The Acting Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer or any appropriate Municipal official submitted the documents to substantiate the relief operations made by the Municipality for the Audit Team to determine whether the procured relief supplies were completely distributed to the intended beneficiaries;
d. The Municipal Budget Officer had submitted to the Auditor a written justification explaining the rationale for the charging of said disbursements; and
e. The concerned official had posted the required information for transparency.

observations.recommendation:
a. Evaluate the necessity of the unimplemented projects, especially those in prior years, and reprogram the same to more important development projects that will cater to the present needs of the constituents;
b. Ensure that all projects funded out of the 20 percent DF will be implemented during the year in order to attain the desired socio-economic development and environmental outcomes.
We also reiterated our recommendation that the Municipal Budget Officer and Acting Municipal Accountant to appropriate expenditures specifically related to the objectives of 20 percent Development Fund in the next budget and refrain from charging expenses that do not contribute to the attainment of desirable socio-economic development and environmental management outcomes of the Municipality.

